"1201":"1201","1245":"1245","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","about 1185":"omkring 1185","Tiverton, Devon, England":"Tiverton, Devon, England","Truro, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Truro, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Hittsleigh, Devon, England":"Hittisleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Huntensleigh Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"1185–1273":"1185–1273","1187–Female":"1187–Overleden","1210–1235":"1210–1235","1210–1245":"1210–1245","1210–Male":"1210–Overleden","1160–1243":"1160–1243","1160–1201":"1160–1201","1187":"1187","1185":"1185","1273":"1273","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1245":"1245","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","about 1185":"circa 1185","Tiverton, Devon, England":"Tiverton, Devon, England","Truro, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Truro, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hittsleigh, Devon, England":"Hittisleigh, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Huntensleigh Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"1185–1273":"1185–1273","1187–Female":"1187–Deceased","1210–1235":"1210–1235","1210–1245":"1210–1245","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1160–1243":"1160–1243","1160–1201":"1160–1201","1187":"1187","1185":"1185","1273":"1273","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1245":"1245","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","about 1185":"about 1185","Tiverton, Devon, England":"Tiverton, Devon, England","Truro, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Truro, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Hittsleigh, Devon, England":"Hittisleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Huntensleigh Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cole","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: usually from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, <i>Coll(e)</i>, <i>Coul(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nicol</i> (see   Nichol   and   Nicholas  ), a common personal name from the mid 13th century onward. English families with this name migrated to Scotland and to Ulster (especially Fermanagh).","English: occasionally perhaps from a different (early) Middle English personal name <i>Col</i>, of native English or Scandinavian origin. Old English <i>Cola</i> was originally a nickname from Old English <i>col</i> ‘coal’ in the sense ‘coal-black (of hair), swarthy’ and is the probable source of most of the examples in Domesday Book. In the northern and eastern counties of England settled by Vikings in the 10th and 11th centuries, alternative sources are Old Norse <i>Kolr</i> and <i>Koli</i> (either from a nickname ‘the swarthy one’ or a short form of names in <i>Kol-</i>), and Old Norse <i>Kollr</i> (from a nickname, perhaps ‘the bald one’).","English: nickname for someone with swarthy skin or black hair, from Middle English <i>col</i>, coul(e) ‘charcoal, coal’ (Old English <i>col</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Colton","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Nottinghamshire): habitational name from any of various places called Colton in England. Examples in Norfolk, Staffordshire, and North Yorkshire are from the Old English personal name <i>Cola</i> (or the cognate Old Norse <i>Koli</i>; see   Cole   2) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. The place so named in Somerset has as its first element the Old English personal name <i>Cūla</i> (of uncertain origin). The one in Cumbria has a river name apparently derived from a Celtic word meaning ‘hazel’. This English name is also common in Ireland; it was the name of a bishop of Derry in 1397. There seems also to have been confusion with   Culliton  .","Scottish and Irish (Monaghan): shortened and altered form of Gaelic <b>Mac Haldan</b>, ‘son of <i>Haldan</i>’, see   Haldane  ."]},{"name":"Colclough","meanings":["English (Staffordshire and Cheshire): habitational name from Cowclough in the parish of Whitworth, Lancashire, earlier recorded as <i>Colleclogh</i>, probably named with the Old English byname <i>Cola</i> (see   Cole   2) + Old English <i>clōh</i> ‘ravine’."]},{"name":"Calcote","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places (in Bedfordshire, Berkshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Northamptonshire, Warwickshire, and elsewhere) named Caldecote or Caldecott, from Old English <i>cald</i> ‘cold’ + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, dwelling’. It has been suggested that in Old English this expression denoted an unattended shelter for wayfarers, although in fact some places with this name were of considerable status by 1086, when they appear in Domesday Book. In some instances this and some of the other shortened forms may have arisen from Calcot in Berkshire, Collacott(s) in Devon, or Calcutt in Wiltshire, in all of which the first element apparently comes from the Old English personal name <i>Cola</i> (see   Cole   2) or the word <i>col</i> ‘(char)coal’, in which case the meaning would be something like ‘coalshed’."]},{"name":"Collignon","meanings":["French and Walloon: from a shortened pet form (see   Cole   and   Colle  ) of the French personal name <i>Nicolas</i> (see   Nicholas  )."]},{"name":"Colling","meanings":["English (northern England and Devon): from the Old Norse personal name <i>Kollungr</i>, a derivative of <i>Koli</i>, or from Old English <i>Colling</i>, a derivative of <i>Cola</i> (see   Cole  ). Alternatively, from a pet form of the personal name <i>Col(l)</i>, a pet form of   Nicholas   (see also   Colin  ).","German: variant of   Kolling   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Collard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Donat, Normand, Octave, Adelard, Aldor, Andre, Armand, Emile, Germaine, Marcel.","English (southern), French, and Walloon: from a diminutive of the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nic(h)olas</i> (see   Cole  ), formed with the Old French suffix <i>-ard</i>."]},{"name":"Coale","meanings":["English: post-medieval form of   Cole  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Coles","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Cole  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Nichol","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Nic(h)ol(e)</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Nic(h)olas</i> (see   Nicholas  ). Compare   Nickel   and   Nicol  .","In some cases also an American shortened and altered form of Greek   Nikolas  , its variant   Nicolas  , or of any of various derivatives of the personal name <i>Nikola(o)s</i> ‘Nicholas’, including <b>Nikolis</b> (see   Nicoli  ). Compare   Nicholas   and   Nicol  ."]},{"name":"Coalson","meanings":["English: patronymic from   Cole  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":30,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":39,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":74,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Cole was born in 1185, in Devon, England, his father, William Cole, was 25 and his mother, Lady Ysabella, was 25. He had at least 3 sons with Edith Burdenville. He died in 1273, in his hometown, at the age of 88."},"et":{"1185–1273":"1185–1273","1187–Female":"1187–Surnud","1210–1235":"1210–1235","1210–1245":"1210–1245","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1160–1243":"1160–1243","1160–1201":"1160–1201","1187":"1187","1185":"1185","1273":"1273","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1201":"1201","1245":"1245","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","about 1185":"umbes 1185","Tiverton, Devon, England":"Tiverton, Devon, England","Truro, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Truro, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hittsleigh, Devon, England":"Hittisleigh, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Huntensleigh Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1185–1273":"1185–1273","1187–Female":"1187–Kuollut","1210–1235":"1210–1235","1210–12